Hi,

I'm trying to create a PDF, which will contain a bunch of images.

These images vary greatly in size. Some of them need to be scaled down to fit the width of the page, which the default scaling strategy does already.  
However, some of them do not need to be scaled at all, but I cannot figure out how to render an image without scaling.

Basically how can I render an image like this?:
![image](https://github.com/QuestPDF/QuestPDF/assets/3437394/f3dcce3a-0df3-47b5-94e5-17a85677d78c)

The above is made with HTML to illustrate what I need.
You can see the page, which has some margins set and the blue border represents the item containing the image. The item fills the entire width of the page, as you'd expect.
The image itself isn't large enough to fill the width of the page, so it just takes up whatever space it needs and no more.
To be clear, I am not interested in drawing the blue border. It's just there for illustrative purposes.

I know the image width and height in pixels, so my first thought was to simply use the `.Width()` container element, but it does not accept pixels as a unit.

The code I have so far is basically just:

```c#
public void Compose(IDocumentContainer container)
{
    container.Page(page =>
    {
        page.Margin(1, Unit.Inch);
        
        page.Content().Column(column =>
        {
           byte[] image = ...; // not important.
           column.Item().Image(image);
        });
    });
}
```

The code works well for large images that are then scaled down to fit the width of the page, but how do I prevent smaller images from scaling up, when I don't know their sizes in any unit supported by QuestPDF?

